		<body>
			<pb n="1"/>
				<p rend="align(right)"><placeName>Charleston</placeName> <date>Sep 18. 1838</date></p>
				<p><addressee>Rev I. Leeser</addressee></p>
			<p rend="indent(1)">My dear Sir</p>
			<p rend="indent(3)">I have duly received yr esteemed Favors of<lb/> <sic>of</sic> the <date>9<hi rend="sup">th</hi> Aug.</date> &#38; <date>5<hi rend="sup">th</hi></date> Inst&#44; &#38; regret much to find that yr health is so<lb/> precarious.  The parcel for <persName>Mr Benjamin</persName> pr S C. is at hand &#38; shall be<lb/> forwarded by first conveyance&#58; that pr <persName>Randoph</persName> has never been received&#44; indeed<lb/> I knew nothing of it until after the Schooner had left yr request as to<lb/> the contribution by a young Lady of yr flock for rebuilding synagogue<lb/> will be most <add>&#63;</add> <sic>fullfilling</sic>.  My time my dear Sir does not<lb/> allow me to be as full in my correspondence with you as I could wish..<lb/>  I would most willingly give you all the aid I could for carrying out<lb/> yr zealous &#38; highly praiseworthy efforts in the cause of our holy religion<lb/> were I differently circumstanced but I have but a very small fraction<lb/> of time to devote even to my family&#44; as to my Father his time<lb/> is so much engrossed with congregational duties&#44; increased<add>&#63;</add> much<lb/> by the epidemic which has been raging in our city&#44; that he<lb/> I am sure&#44; could not give that attention to the holy work necessary<lb/> I would therefore suggest the propriety of yr opening a correspondence<lb/> with a highly reputable gentleman of our congregation&#44; one of<lb/> much leisure &#38; sufficient val<add>&#63;</add>.  I refer to <persName>Major I. Lazarus</persName>&#44; who is<lb/> one of the Trustees of the Syngagogue.  I do think he will with much<lb/> pleasure take charge of those duties which have been in our<lb/> hands&#44; &#38; all such which may be necessary to carry out yr zealous</p>
			<pb n="2"/>
				<p>efforts to enlighten the <add>&#63;</add> generation of Israelites in the<lb/> principles of our holy religion.  I trust that you will view<lb/> this suggestion of change only in a friendly light We<lb/> are unable from circumstances to do that justice to your calls<lb/> which our feelings prompt <del>as well</del> &#38; which they richly merit<lb/> our Hazan has had leave of absence in consequence of the unhealthy<lb/> condition of our city&#44; a very large number of strangers have fallen<lb/> victims among whom some few of <placeName>Israel</placeName>&#58; <persName>Mr Poznanski</persName> is at<lb/> present in <placeName>Greenville SoCa.</placeName> comfortably situated on his return I will<lb/> place in his hands yr two last letters &#38; doubt not they will <sic>received</sic><lb/> due attention.  With my best wishes that the ensuing year<lb/> will be one full of good to you &#38; all <placeName>Israel</placeName></p>
			<p rend="indent(5)">I remain</p>
			<p rend="indent(6)">yr Friend</p>
			<p rend="indent(6)"><persName role="author">I. N. Hart</persName></p>
			<pb n="4"/>
				<p><addressee>Revd Isaac. Leeser</addressee></p>
			<p rend="indent(1)">Pastor Hebrew Congregation</p>
			<p rend="indent(3)"><placeName>Philadelphia</placeName></p>
				<p>single</p>
				<p><persName>Smith Moury</persName> <add>&#63;</add></p>
			<p rend="indent(1)">agent</p>
